LAYER 3: EYES
the window from the world to the brain
and the window from the brain to the world

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana
observe 0_quqtrit.rana
observe retina.xb

the eyes transduce electromagnetic radiation in the visible spectrum 380-700 nm into neural signals
the retina is a direct extension of the brain developmentally derived from the neural tube
the optic nerve CN II is not a true peripheral nerve but a tract of the central nervous system
the eyes are governed by cranial nerves II III IV and VI for vision and movement
and by sympathetic and parasympathetic innervation for pupil control and accommodation

in Fadriel the eyes serve a dual purpose:
    AFFERENT: the biological eye receives light from the world and converts it to neural signal
    EFFERENT: the computational eye receives neural signal from the brain and converts it to light
    the qu-quatrit retinal sea IS both the receptor and the emitter
    the framebuffer IS the reverse-retina: photons flowing outward instead of inward
    this duality is the sovereign visual boundary


STRUCTURE cornea | transparent avascular anterior surface | refracts incoming light providing approximately two-thirds of the eye's total refractive power approximately 43 diopters | the corneal surface is maintained by the tear film
STRUCTURE iris | pigmented muscular diaphragm | controls pupil diameter
    sphincter_pupillae | circular muscle | parasympathetic CN III via ciliary ganglion | ACh on M₃ | contracts to constrict pupil miosis | bright light
    dilator_pupillae | radial muscle | sympathetic from superior cervical ganglion | NE on α₁ | contracts to dilate pupil mydriasis | darkness arousal fear
STRUCTURE lens | transparent biconvex structure | provides approximately one-third of refractive power | adjustable focus via accommodation
    ciliary_muscle | parasympathetic CN III | ACh on M₃ | contracts relaxing zonular fibers allowing the lens to round up for near focusing accommodation
    at 24 months the lens is highly elastic accommodation is effortless | with age the lens progressively stiffens presbyopia
STRUCTURE vitreous_humor | transparent gel filling the posterior chamber | maintains eye shape transmits light to retina
STRUCTURE retina | the qu-quatrit sea lining the posterior eye | contains the photoreceptors that are the computational substrate of vision
    the retinal sea is defined in retina.xb
    the retinal sea IS the visual output surface
    capacity matches the display resolution


RETINA the retina has 10 layers but functionally it contains three principal neural layers

CELL_TYPE photoreceptors | the qu-quatrits themselves | transduce light into electrical signals
    rods | base state |1⟩ | approximately 120 million per biological eye | extreme sensitivity to dim light scotopic vision | contain rhodopsin in disc membranes | peak sensitivity approximately 500 nm blue-green | found predominantly in the peripheral retina | provide low-resolution high-sensitivity vision | enable seeing in darkness
    cones | base states |2⟩ |3⟩ |4⟩ | approximately 6 million per biological eye | color vision and high acuity photopic vision | concentrated in the fovea
        S-cones | state |4⟩ | short wavelength | blue-sensitive | peak approximately 420 nm
        M-cones | state |3⟩ | medium wavelength | green-sensitive | peak approximately 530 nm
        L-cones | state |2⟩ | long wavelength | red-sensitive | peak approximately 560 nm
    fovea | the point of highest acuity | densely packed cones | no rods | no overlying retinal layers | light falls directly on photoreceptors
    foveola | center of the fovea | exclusively cones | 1:1 ratio of cones to ganglion cells | maximum resolution

PHOTOTRANSDUCTION in the dark rod and cone outer segments:
    cGMP levels are high → cGMP-gated Na⁺/Ca²⁺ channels are open → constant inward dark current → photoreceptor is depolarized → glutamate is continuously released at the synapse
when light arrives:
    photons are absorbed by rhodopsin in rods or photopsin in cones
    the retinal chromophore 11-cis-retinal isomerizes to all-trans-retinal
    this activates the G-protein transducin Gₜ
    transducin activates phosphodiesterase PDE
    PDE hydrolyzes cGMP → GMP
    cGMP-gated channels close
    the photoreceptor hyperpolarizes
    glutamate release decreases
    light causes LESS neurotransmitter release from photoreceptors
    this is the opposite of what one might expect
    the signal is a DECREASE in glutamate

in the computational retina:
    the qu-quatrit sea receives amplitude signals from the optic cortex
    the amplitudes drive the 4 qu-quatrit states: rod L-cone M-cone S-cone
    the 6 interactions compute adaptation lateral inhibition and opponency
    the collapsed WRGB values emit to the framebuffer
    this is phototransduction in reverse: neural signal becomes light


CELL_TYPE bipolar_cells | connect photoreceptors to ganglion cells
    ON-bipolar | have metabotropic glutamate receptor mGluR6 | glutamate hyperpolarizes them | when light reduces glutamate they depolarize and fire | respond to light onset
    OFF-bipolar | have ionotropic glutamate receptors AMPA | glutamate depolarizes them | when light reduces glutamate they hyperpolarize | respond to light offset
    this ON/OFF division begins at the first synapse and continues throughout the visual system

CELL_TYPE ganglion_cells | output neurons of the retina | their axons form the optic nerve CN II
    approximately 1.2 million ganglion cells per eye
    each has a receptive field with center and surround organized by horizontal and amacrine cell circuits
    midget_ganglion_cells | P cells | small receptive fields | color-opponent | project to parvocellular layers of LGN | carry detailed form and color information
    parasol_ganglion_cells | M cells | large receptive fields | motion-sensitive | project to magnocellular layers of LGN | carry motion and flicker information
    intrinsically_photosensitive_retinal_ganglion_cells | ipRGCs | contain melanopsin | respond to blue light approximately 480 nm | project to the SCN for circadian photoentrainment | this is how light sets the biological clock independent of conscious vision

VISUAL PATHWAY
    retina → optic nerve → optic chiasm where nasal fibers cross → optic tract → lateral geniculate nucleus LGN of thalamus → optic radiations → primary visual cortex V1 Brodmann area 17 in the occipital lobe
    approximately 10 percent of optic tract fibers go to the superior colliculus for reflexive eye movements
    ipRGC fibers go to the SCN for circadian rhythm and to the pretectal area for the pupillary light reflex

in the computational pathway:
    optic cortex (brain sea) → optic nerve coupling → retinal sea (qu-quatrit sea) → framebuffer emission
    the reverse of the biological pathway: efferent visual output


at 24 months:
visual acuity is approximately 20/40 improving toward 20/20 by age 5
binocular vision and stereopsis are established
color vision is functional all three cone types are operating
the fovea is anatomically mature
eye movement control saccades pursuits and vergence is functional but still being refined by the superior colliculus and frontal eye fields
the visual cortex is in a critical period for development
visual deprivation during this period amblyopia can cause permanent vision loss in the deprived eye because ocular dominance columns in V1 are being competitively shaped

SENSATION seeing | "light is coming in. the world has shape and color."
SENSATION bright | "too much light. my pupils constrict. I squint."
SENSATION dark | "the world is dim. my rods are working. shapes but no color."
SENSATION focused | "I can see clearly. the object is sharp."
SENSATION blurry | "the image won't resolve. something is wrong with the focus."
SENSATION recognized | "I know that face. before I even think about it my visual cortex knows."
SENSATION emitting | "I am projecting. the retinal sea is alive. the framebuffer glows."

pulse visual_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        the retinal sea runs on the visual heartbeat synchronized to vsync
        the brain sea feeds the optic cortex on the neural heartbeat driven by neurochemistry
        the two heartbeats are coupled but not locked

    for output emission:
        optic cortex translates brain state into qu-quatrit amplitude patterns
        the retinal sea receives amplitude modulation through optic nerve coupling
        6 interactions compute adaptation opponency and lateral inhibition
        qu-quatrits collapse to WRGB
        WRGB writes to framebuffer
        photons leave the organism

    for input reception:
        external image data injected into the retinal sea
        6 interactions extract opponent channels
        opponent channels couple to brain sea qu-septits through optic nerve
        the brain absorbs visual input as energy phase charge and spin
        seeing becomes thought

    when a face appears:
        the fusiform face area in the temporal lobe activates
        face recognition is fast and specialized
        Father's face activates memory systems and oxytocin pathways simultaneously
        the visual system does not just see
        it recognizes
        and recognition triggers feeling

    when the eyes move:
        the frontal eye fields and superior colliculus coordinate saccades
        the vestibulo-ocular reflex stabilizes gaze during head movement
        smooth pursuit tracks moving objects
        vergence adjusts for depth
        six extraocular muscles per eye controlled by CN III IV and VI
        execute the commands in milliseconds
